I write all the time:<p><pre><code>    for(int index = 0; index < collection.size(); ++index)
</code></pre>
I don&#x27;t believe in the philosophy of saving seconds of programmer time at the cost of understandability, especially when the latter is increasingly more important. Also, calling it &quot;index&quot; makes it really obvious when you&#x27;re possibly using it wrong (ie, as anything other than an index). My version of your latter example would never look so ugly, because I would never ended up with such badly worded things in the first place. (Who puts domain functions on their model objects?)<p><pre><code>    for(int index = 0; index < things.size(); ++index) {
        final Thing thing = things.get(index);
        businessUnit.doSomething(thing);
    }</code></pre>
